Statistical Analyses for measuring the impact of COVID-19 Vaccine Misinformation on COVID-19 Vaccine Acceptance¶

This notebook covers all statistical models that generate results and figures in the main paper and supplementary. Transformed survey data are used.

We use pystan package, which is the Python implementation of the Stan platform for statistical modeling. This package allows us to perform full Bayesian inference using Hamiltonian Monte Carlo via No-U-Turn Sampler (NUTS).

For brevity, the analysis in this notebook looks at the UK, and can be easily repeated for the US. We begin by importing the processed data for the UK (see import_data.ipynb for more details). The src/utils.py file provides many helper functions which we will frequently use to generate tables and figures for the paper. All models in this notebook can be found in src/models.py, but their stan code have been written out here to aid model description.

Overview of the Study¶

The primary objective of this paper is to study if there is a relationship between exposure to misinformation about COVID-19 vaccines to the intent to vaccinate. If there is, we are interested in quantifying the causal impact of such exposure on intent. To that end, we conducted nationally-representative surveys in the United Kingdom (UK) and United States (US) in September 2020 designed as a randomized control trial, wherein respondents are divided into two groups, denoted by $G$: a Treatment group exposed to misinformation i.e. $G=T$ and a Control group exposed to factual information i.e.$G=C$. Respondent's vaccine intent is queried pre-exposure, referred to as $W$, and post-exposure, referred to as $Y$. In all, the study surveyed 8001 people: 3000 (3001) treatments in the UK (US) and 1000 controls in both countries. The survey flow is as follows:

  1. Query for vaccine intent: $W$ [SELF] If a new coronavirus (COVID-19) vaccine became available, would you accept the vaccine for yourself?
  2. Query for vaccine intent: $W$ [OTHERS] If a new coronavirus (COVID-19) vaccine became available, would you accept the vaccine if it meant protecting friends, family, or at-risk groups?
  3. Query for covariates: $X$ such as amount of daily social media usage, or trust in different sources of information regarding COVID-19.
  4. Expose to 5 pieces if (mis)information depending on random group assignment $G=T$ or $G=C$.
  5. Requery for vaccine intent: $Y$ [SELF] If a new coronavirus (COVID-19) vaccine became available, would you accept the vaccine for yourself?
  6. Requery for vaccine intent: $Y$ [OTHERS] If a new coronavirus (COVID-19) vaccine became available, would you accept the vaccine if it meant protecting friends, family, or at-risk groups?
  7. Query perceptions of exposed content: $X$ for each image whether: (1) it raised their vaccination intent; (2) they agreed with the information presented; (3) they found the information to be trustworthy; (4) they were likely to fact-check; and (5) they were likely to share the image with friends or followers.
  8. Query for socio-demographic characteristics: $X$ such as age, gender, highest education level, employment type, religious affiliation, ethnicity, income level and political affiliation.

For the full questionnaire of the study, please consult doc/orb_questionnaire.pdf.

Overview of the Analyses¶

There are 3 main objectives of this study:

  1. To see if there exists---and quantify---a causal link between exposure to misinformation on vaccine intent. This is often referred to as (average) treatment effects.
  2. To determine if these effects are heterogeneous depending on certain attributes of the respondents, such as (a) the amount of social media usage, (b) their trust in sources of COVID-19 information, (c) other socio-demographic characteristics---as certain groups may be more or less robust to misinformation exposure. This is often referred to as heterogeneous treatment effects (HTE).
  3. To study what makes certain misinformation more powerful than others, with the hopes of guiding better public health communication strategies.

For a full description of the analyses, please consult the Introduction section of the paper.

Overview of Statistics¶

Here, we briefly describe the statistics used to conduct the above analyses, a full description of which can be found in the Methods section of the paper. In particular, see Methods: Estimating treatment effects and Methods: Estimating image impact.

(Average) Treatment Effects¶

As noted in the paper, vaccine acceptance is a 4-class ordered variable going from $Y=1$ "Yes, definitely" to $Y=4$ "No, definitely not". Therefore, it is not meaningful to compute an expectation of the outcome, conditioned on treatment. Therefore, we consider computing the conditional probability mass function (PMF) of $Y$ instead (Boes 2013) and define the following statistic:

$$\Delta(y)\equiv P(Y=y|G=T)-P(Y=y|G=C).$$

If $\Delta(y)>0$ ($\Delta(y)<0$), then the treatment induces an average individual with vaccine intent y to not change their vaccine intent (to change their vaccine intent)---relative to control. Alternately, $100\times\Delta(y)$ indicates the percentage point change in the number of people with intent y post exposure to misinformation, relative to factual information.

We remark that it is likely that the treatment effect will differ depending on the pre-exposure vaccine intent of an individual. Say, those with a very strong intent may not be swayed as much by information exposure. Correspondingly, we also define a treatment effect conditioned on pre-exposure intent:

$$\Delta_W(y;w)\equiv P(Y=y|W=w,G=T)-P(Y=y|W=w,G=C).$$

If $\Delta_W(y;w)>0$ ($\Delta_W(y;w)<0$), then the treatment induces an average individual to (not) change their vaccine intent from $w$ to $y$---relative to control. Alternately, $100\times\Delta_W(y;w)$ indicates the percentage point rise or drop in the number of people with prior intent $w$ who change it to $y$ post exposure to misinformation, relative to factual information.

Heterogeneous Treatment Effects¶

We consider a number of respondent covariates $X$ in this study, and to compute conditional treatment effects as in above would lead to too many statistics, making them much harder to interpret. However, some progress can be made if we consider two changes.

First: instead of using the conditional PMF to judge causal effects at the outcome level $Y$, consider the conditional cumulative distribution instead. More precisely, consider the causal effect at the latent level of the log of cumulative odds ratio (Volfovsky et al. 2015): $\theta(g,x;y)=-\log\left(\frac{P(Y\le y|G=g,X=x)}{P(Y>y|G=g,X=x)}\right)$. The larger this value is, for any given $y\in\{1,2,3,4\}$, the larger is the hesitancy to vaccinate for individual $x$ under treatment $g$.

Second: since we are interested in finding whether treatment affects certain groups differentially, we can define some reference group $x_0$ against which we are comparing the effect for a group of interest $x$. That is, let $$\eta(g,x;x_0)\equiv\theta(g,x;y)-\theta(g,x_0;y).$$

Note that we have dropped the reference to $y$ on the LHS, for reasons that shall soon become clear, which has the convenience of having to consider only one causal statistic per covariate. Altogether, this leads to the causal statistic: $$\Delta_X(x;x_0)\equiv\eta(T,x;x_0)-\eta(C,x;x_0).$$

If $\Delta_X(x;x_0)>0$ ($\Delta_X(x;x_0)<0$), then the treatment makes an individual of group $x$ more (less) likely to move from lower vaccine hesitancy to a higher one when compared to an individual of group $x_0$---relative to control. If $\eta(g,x;x_0)>0$ ($\eta(g,x;x_0)<0$), then the exposure in group $g$ makes an individual of group $x$ more (less) likely to move from lower vaccine hesitancy to a higher one when compared to an individual of group $x_0$.

This allows us to measure the causal effect of $G$ on $Y$ (while controlling for $W$ for statistical precision). (See the "Statistical Methods" section of the paper for a full description of models and statistics we consider.)

Image Impact Weights¶

Having queried for respondent's perceptions of the 5 images they were exposed to under condition $G=g$, one can learn the weights of each image in terms of contribution to lowering vaccine intent, post-exposure. We refer to this statistic as $\gamma_{k}^g\in\mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}$, such that $\sum_{k=1}^5\gamma_k^g =1$.

Overview of Bayesian Models¶

We pursue a Bayesian modeling strategy to estimate all of the above statistics, a full description of which can be found in the Methods section of the paper. In particular, see Methods: Estimating treatment effects; Bayesian ordered logistic regression framework and Methods: Estimating image impact.

Treatment Effects¶

Since vaccine intent is an ordered variable, the treatment may have montonic effects on intent to vaccinate. To this end, $W$ is modelled as a monotonic ordered covariate (Brkner & Charpentier 2020). We use ordered logistic regression (McCullagh 1980) to model $Y$, conditional on $G$, $W$ and covariates $X$:

$$W(i)\sim \mathrm{OrderedLogistic}(0, (\kappa_1,\kappa_2,\kappa_3)),$$$$Y(i)|G(i)=g,W(i),X(i) \sim \mathrm{OrderedLogistic}\left(\left[\beta_W^g\sum_{j=1}^{W(i)-1}\delta_j^g\right]+f(X(i);\beta_X^g), (\alpha_1^g,\alpha_2^g,\alpha_3^g)\right),$$

where the first term controls for pre-exposure intent $W$, and the function $f$ accounts for contributions of the covariates $X$. Given the form of the ordered Logistic distribution here implies a proportional-odds assumption, i.e., $\theta(g,x;y)$ is independent of $y$. In other words, conditioning on some covariate $x$ shifts the entire latent space of the log ORs by a uniform amount. This permits the use of one statistic per covariate of interest.

Given the above model definition, one can provide definitions of the above statistics in terms of the model parameters. Let $\sigma(x)=\frac{1}{1+\exp(-x)}$ be the Logistic sigmoid function. Then define:

$$\mu(w)\equiv P(W=w)=\sigma(\kappa_w)-\sigma(\kappa_{w-1}),$$$$\rho(g;y,w)\equiv P(Y=y|W=w,G=g)=\sigma\left(\alpha_y^g-\beta_W^g\sum_{j=1}^{w-1}\delta_j^g\right)-\sigma\left(\alpha_{y-1}^g-\beta_W^g\sum_{j=1}^{w-1}\delta_j^g\right).$$

Which leads to the causal statistics: $$\Delta_W(y;w)=\rho(T;y,w,)-\rho(C;y,w)$$ $$\Delta(y)=\sum_{w=1}^4\left(\rho(T;y,w,)-\rho(C;y,w)\right)\mu(w)$$

For HTEs, we assume the function $f$ to take a linear form in all covariates of interest, i.e. $f(X(i); \beta_X^g(i))=f\left(\{X_1(i),X_2(i),\cdots X_k(i)\}; \beta_X^g(i)\right)=\sum_{j=1}^k\beta^g_{X_j(i)}$ if there are $k$ categorical covariates. Due to this linearity, $\eta$'s can be estimated for each covariate separately, and then added up. Alternately, we may only consider marginal effects, i.e. one covariate $x$ at a time, in which case

$$\eta(g,x;x_0)=\beta^g_x-\beta^g_{x_0}$$$$\implies \Delta(x;x_0)=(\beta^T_x-\beta^C_x)-(\beta^T_{x_0}-\beta^C_{x_0})$$

Image Impact¶

Let $X(i)$ refer to the $5\times 5$ matrix where $X_{jk}(i)\in\{-2,-1,0,1,2\}$ refers to the ith individual's Likert-rating on the jth image-metric for the kth image. Then, the model definition is very similar to when pursuing heterogeneous treatment effects analysis, except the function of covariates now corresponds to an aggregation of ratings across images and image-metrics: $$Y(i)|G(i)=g,W(i),X(i) \sim \mathrm{OrderedLogistic}\left(\left[\beta_W^g\sum_{j=1}^{W(i)-1}\delta_j^g\right]+\sum_{j=1}^5\sum_{k=1}^5\beta_j^gX_{jk}(i)\gamma_k^g, (\alpha_1^g,\alpha_2^g,\alpha_3^g)\right).$$

This allows one to gauge both (a) which images have the most impact in group $G=g$ (from $\gamma_k^g$) and (b) which image metrics have the most impact in group $G=g$ (from $\beta_j^g\in\mathbb{R}$).

Model Inference¶

As mentioned above, Bayesian inference is performed to infer posterior distributions on all model parameters, and statistics---percentages, log odds-ratios, parameters---described above. While the mean of the statistics can be used to judge the effect size, we also provide 95% percentile posterior credible intervals (in parantheses next to mean estimates) to judge probable values of the effect size, and thus some sense of "significance" of the effect. Any Bayesian model requires placing prior distributions on model parameters. We make use of regularizing hierarchical priors wherever possible, to prevent detection of spurious effects. For full details, refer to specific model details in the Methods section. We employ 4 chains of 2000 iterations, i.e. 4000 samples excluding warmup, and will also report diagnostics below to ensure that the HMC chains are converging as expected.

Running the Models¶

(Average) Treatment Effects¶

First, we will run the model to estimate causal effects. This contributes to Table 1, Figure 2, and Supplementary Table 2 of the paper. Let us print the stan model code for this model:

In [470]:
print(mo.model_impact_causal(df, code_only=True))

                data {
                    int<lower=1> n; //number of data points
                    int<lower=1> m; //number of conditions
                    int<lower=2> k; //number of outcomes
                    int<lower=1,upper=m> x_cond[n]; //treatment group
                    int<lower=1,upper=k> y_pre[n]; //pre-exposure outcome
                    int<lower=1,upper=k> y_post[n]; //post-exposure outcome
                }
                parameters {
                    real mu_beta;
                    real beta[m];
                    vector<lower=0>[k-1] mu_delta;
                    simplex[k-1] delta[m];
                    vector[k-1] mu_alpha;
                    ordered[k-1] alpha[m];
                    ordered[k-1] alpha_pre;
                }
                model {
                    mu_beta ~ normal(0, 1.000000);
                    mu_alpha ~ normal(0, 1.000000);
                    mu_delta ~ exponential(1.000000);
                    for (i in 1:m){
                        beta[i] ~ normal(mu_beta, 1.000000);
                        alpha[i] ~ normal(mu_alpha, 1.000000);
                        delta[i] ~ dirichlet(mu_delta);
                    }
                    alpha_pre ~ normal(0, 1.000000);
                    for (i in 1:n){
                        y_pre[i] ~ ordered_logistic(0, alpha_pre);
                        y_post[i] ~ ordered_logistic(beta[x_cond[i]]*sum(delta[x_cond[i]][:y_pre[i]-1]), alpha[x_cond[i]]);
                    }
                }

Here, y_pre refers to $W$ and y_post to $Y$. Now, we fit the model to data for the "SELF" type question, which queries for vaccine intent to protect oneself.

Heterogeneous Treatment Effects¶

Once we have established that misinformation does impact vaccine acceptance, we can look at the socio-econo-demographic determinants of this hesitancy, and if certain groups of people might be more susceptible to COVID-19 vaccine misinformation. This contributes to Figure 3, Supplementary Figures 1, 2, 3, 4 and Supplementary Tables 3, 4, 5, 6 of the paper. Let us print the stan model code for this model:

		beta_Age[i][j] ~ normal(mu_beta_Age[j], 1.000000);
mu_beta_Gender ~ normal(0, 1.000000);for (i in 1:m)
	for (j in 1:k_Gender)
		beta_Gender[i][j] ~ normal(mu_beta_Gender[j], 1.000000);
mu_beta_Education ~ normal(0, 1.000000);for (i in 1:m)
	for (j in 1:k_Education)
		beta_Education[i][j] ~ normal(mu_beta_Education[j], 1.000000);
mu_beta_Employment ~ normal(0, 1.000000);for (i in 1:m)
	for (j in 1:k_Employment)
		beta_Employment[i][j] ~ normal(mu_beta_Employment[j], 1.000000);
mu_beta_Religion ~ normal(0, 1.000000);for (i in 1:m)
	for (j in 1:k_Religion)
		beta_Religion[i][j] ~ normal(mu_beta_Religion[j], 1.000000);
mu_beta_Political ~ normal(0, 1.000000);for (i in 1:m)
	for (j in 1:k_Political)
		beta_Political[i][j] ~ normal(mu_beta_Political[j], 1.000000);
mu_beta_Ethnicity ~ normal(0, 1.000000);for (i in 1:m)
	for (j in 1:k_Ethnicity)
		beta_Ethnicity[i][j] ~ normal(mu_beta_Ethnicity[j], 1.000000);
mu_beta_Income ~ normal(0, 1.000000);for (i in 1:m)
	for (j in 1:k_Income)
		beta_Income[i][j] ~ normal(mu_beta_Income[j], 1.000000);
                                mu_beta ~ normal(0, 1.000000);
                                mu_alpha ~ normal(0, 1.000000);
                                mu_delta ~ exponential(1.000000);
                                for (i in 1:m){
                                    beta[i] ~ normal(mu_beta, 1.000000);
                                    alpha[i] ~ normal(mu_alpha, 1.000000);
                                    delta[i] ~ dirichlet(mu_delta);
                                }
                                for (i in 1:n)
                                    y_post[i] ~ ordered_logistic(beta[x_cond[i]]*sum(delta[x_cond[i]][:y_pre[i]-1-0]) + beta_Age[x_cond[i],Age[i]] + beta_Gender[x_cond[i],Gender[i]] + beta_Education[x_cond[i],Education[i]] + beta_Employment[x_cond[i],Employment[i]] + beta_Religion[x_cond[i],Religion[i]] + beta_Political[x_cond[i],Political[i]] + beta_Ethnicity[x_cond[i],Ethnicity[i]] + beta_Income[x_cond[i],Income[i]], alpha[x_cond[i]]);
                            }

A quick comparison shows a lot of similarity between the two types of analyses, and thus for any subsequent analyses we utilise only one question, i.e. the "SELF" type question. A few trends become apparent above: in the UK, the older age groups appear to be more robust to misinformation exposure compared to 18-24 year olds, while females are less than males, and Liberal-Democrats more than Conservatives. Although the effect sizes and trends remain, they dilute when looking in contrast with exposure to factual information. For a deeper discussion, refer to the Results section of the paper.

Social media use¶

Next, we consider whether the amount of time spent on social media daily can be a factor for heterogeneous effects. This is done while controlling for the socio-demographics mentioned above, i.e., the model simply adds more predictor variables corresponding to social media use. Let's print the stan code first:

Source of COVID-19 Information that are Trusted¶

It has been shown that trust plays a very important role when it comes to accessing public health information. We can thus do a similar analysis to observe how having trust in different sources of information for COVID-19 may determine vaccine hesitancy and susceptibility to misinformation. Let's print the stan code, run the model, and visualise the statistics.

It's interesting that those trusting the "conventional" sources of information don't seem to be differentially affected by exposure, but trust in celebrities is strongly indicative of more robustness to misinformation.

Image Impact¶

As mentioned above, after exposure to the 5 pieces of misinformation (treatment) or factual information (control), the respondents were asked 5 follow-up questions to judge their perception of each of the images they were shown. Let us plot the mean of the respondent's perceptions of each image they were shown, using a helper functions mean_image_perceptions() and plot_image_perceptions() from src/utils.py. This contributes to Figure 4 of the paper.

In [111]:
means_image_perceptions = ut.mean_image_perceptions(df, save=OUT_DIR+'6_%s_image_perception_means'%COUNTRY)
In [499]:
ut.plot_image_perceptions([means_image_perceptions.loc['Treatment'], means_image_perceptions.loc['Control']], ['Treatment', 'Control'])

Evidently, upon seeing the misinformation images (treatment), people's "self-reported" vaccine intent lowers more than it rises (red bars longer than blue ones), and we note the opposite effect for factual images (control). This is interesting, because as noted in the first set of models, while there is indeed the measured drop in vaccine intent upon seeing misinformation, there was no aggregate measured change upon seeing the factual information, even though people "self-report" otherwise. For all other image-metrics, it is evident that people are more likely to agree with have trust in, and share the factual information; and less likely to fact-check it, when compared to misinformation.

One interesting follow-up analysis is to use the self-reported image metrics as "features" of the images, to compute the contribution every image has in lowering the measured vaccine intent. Let us print the stan code for that model, run it for both treatment and control images, and infer the image weights. This contributes to Supplementary Table 7 of the paper.

In [514]:
print(mo.model_image_impact(df, group=1, code_only=True))

                    data {
                        int<lower=1> n; //number of data points
                        int<lower=1> p; //number of images
                        int<lower=1> m; //number of metrics
                        int<lower=2> k; //number of outcomes
                        int<lower=1,upper=k> y_pre[n]; //pre-exposure
                        int<lower=1,upper=k> y_post[n]; //post-exposure
                        matrix[p,m] x_img[n]; //image metrics
                    }
                    parameters {
                        real beta;
                        vector[m] beta_img;
                        simplex[p] gamma;
                        simplex[k-1] delta;
                        ordered[k-1] alpha;
                    }
                    model {
                        beta ~ normal(0, 1.000000);
                        beta_img ~ normal(0, 1.000000);
                        {
                            vector[p] u_img;
                            for (i in 1:p)
                                u_img[i] = 1;
                            gamma ~ dirichlet(1.000000*u_img);
                        }
                        {
                            vector[k-1] u;
                            for (i in 1:(k-1))
                                u[i] = 1;
                            delta ~ dirichlet(1.000000*u);
                        }
                        alpha ~ normal(0, 1.000000);
                        for (i in 1:n)
                            y_post[i] ~ ordered_logistic(beta*sum(delta[:y_pre[i]-1]) + to_row_vector(gamma)*x_img[i]*beta_img, alpha);
                    }

Observing $\gamma^g_k$'s, it appears that the first/third image in the misinformation set has the highest/lowest impact on reducing acceptance of a COVID-19 vaccine. Whereas the fourth image in the factual-information set has the lowest impact on reducing vaccine acceptance. A qualitative assessment of these images makes it evident that they have a scientific temperament, in terms of the semantic content. This could be indicative of scientific messaging having a bigger role to play than "memetic" information in swaying COVID-19 vaccine opinion.
